{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17474992","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17474992"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:27:31+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:27:31+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12478"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12478","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12478"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.2,0.52,0.18,0.06,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4985"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"59551"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4985","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4985"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12478"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"44961"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1036"},{"type":"tags","id":"1641"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"2544"},{"type":"tags","id":"2602"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4897"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"8118"},{"type":"tags","id":"9740"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8245"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9703"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14129"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14370"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15603"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18486"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18652"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42762"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44129"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"59551","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/59551"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA three-year-old boy presents to the Emergency Department with a six-month history of progressive fatigue and shortness of breath during physical activity. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. His parent reports that he has been sweating excessively. When playing with his brother, he sits in a squatting position after five minutes and his lips appear blue during this time.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell. His pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure 90/60 mmHg, respiratory rate 30/min, SpO2 88% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. He weighs 10 kg. His apex beat is palpable in the fourth intercostal space, and there is a left parasternal heave. His heart sounds are dual, with a systolic murmur present in the second intercostal space. His chest demonstrates abnormal bronchial breath sounds. An ECG, echocardiogram and chest X-ray were performed.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is most likely to be found on his chest X-ray?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Increased pulmonary vascular markings","Right ventricular hypertrophy with upturned cardiac apex","Egg-on-a-string appearance of the heart","Rib notching due to collateral vessels","Shift of mediastinum"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe presentation of this patient is consistent with Tetralogy of Fallot, a congenital heart defect that consists of pulmonary outflow obstruction, ventricular septal defect, overriding aorta, and right ventricular hypertrophy. This patient is exhibiting classical \u0027Tet spells\u0027, which are most common in infants. Tetralogy of Fallot is associated with fatigue, shortness of breath, and cyanosis, often during physical activity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERight ventricular hypertrophy with upturned cardiac apex\u003C/strong\u003E is a characteristic chest X-ray finding in Tetralogy of Fallot, giving the classic \u0027boot-shaped\u0027 heart appearance. The hypertrophied right ventricle causes the apex of the heart to lift and point upward, resembling the toe of a boot. The lung fields typically appear oligemic due to decreased pulmonary blood flow.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreased pulmonary vascular markings\u003C/strong\u003E are typically seen in conditions where there is increased blood flow to the lungs, such as left-to-right shunts or pulmonary hypertension. This is not characteristic of Tetralogy of Fallot, which is characterized by decreased pulmonary blood flow.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn \u003Cstrong\u003Eegg-on-a-string appearance of the heart\u003C/strong\u003E is typically seen in transposition of the great arteries, where the aorta arises from the right ventricle and the pulmonary artery arises from the left ventricle, leading to parallel circulations.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERib notching due to collateral vessels\u003C/strong\u003E is typically seen in coarctation of the aorta, where there is a narrowing of the aortic arch and collateral vessels develop to bypass the obstruction. This leads to notching of the ribs due to increased blood flow through the intercostal arteries.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Eshift of mediastinum\u003C/strong\u003E is not a characteristic finding in Tetralogy of Fallot. Mediastinal shift can occur in conditions such as pneumothorax, pleural effusion, or lung collapse, but is not typically associated with this congenital heart defect.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn summary, the clinical presentation of cyanosis, fatigue, and dyspnoea, along with the characteristic \u0027Tet spells\u0027 and physical examination findings, strongly suggest Tetralogy of Fallot. The most likely chest X-ray finding in this condition would be right ventricular hypertrophy with an upturned cardiac apex, reflecting the underlying pathophysiology.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The boot-shaped heart with right ventricular hypertrophy causing an upturned cardiac apex is characteristic of Tetralogy of Fallot on chest X-ray.","Tetralogy of Fallot typically presents with cyanosis, fatigue, and dyspnoea, often exacerbated by physical activity.","\u0027Tet spells\u0027, characterized by increased cyanosis and squatting, are common in infants with Tetralogy of Fallot."],"references":["Diaz-Frias J, Guillaume M. Tetralogy of Fallot. [Updated 2022 Jan 18]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2022 Jan-.","Oldroyd SH, Manek G, Sankari A, et al. Pulmonary Hypertension. [Updated 2022 Nov 3]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2022 Jan-.","Law MA, Tivakaran VS. Coarctation of the Aorta. [Updated 2022 Aug 8]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2022 Jan-."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"44961"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12478"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"44961","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/44961"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-08T13:43:23+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-08T13:45:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4985"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"59551"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"